18, ᾗ 1. Dite patre. Dis Pater was conspicuous in the old Latin pantheon as the god of the dead, although in Caesar's time he had been ousted by Pluto, who was accepted by the Romans as a deity under Greek influence. Caesar recognized one of the Gallie gods as being like Dis Pater and called him by the Latin name.
